Here's a scene that plays out thousands of times a day: someone's hungry, they pull out their phone, they google "restaurants near me." Your restaurant shows up. They tap through to your website. And then one of two things happens.

Either they find what they need in 10 seconds — your menu, your hours, a way to book or order — and they become a customer. Or they hit a slow-loading page, a PDF menu that's impossible to read on a phone, or outdated hours, and they tap back to Google and pick the next place on the list.

72% of restaurant searches happen on mobile. Your website has about 10 seconds to convert a hungry person into a paying customer. Here's what it needs to do that job.

## 1. A real menu (not a PDF)

This is the single most important thing on your restaurant website, and it's where most restaurants fail. You upload a PDF of your printed menu and call it done. But here's what that looks like on a phone: a tiny, unreadable document that requires pinching and zooming. Most people won't bother.

Your menu needs to be actual HTML text on the page. Readable without zooming. Organized by category. With prices visible. Bonus: when your menu is real text instead of a PDF, Google can read it too — which means someone searching for "best tacos near me" might actually find you.

Updating an HTML menu is also faster than redesigning a PDF every time you change a price or add a seasonal dish. Your web developer can set it up so you can make menu changes yourself, or you can send updates and get them posted the same day.

## 2. Online ordering or reservation links

If someone is on your website at 9 PM deciding where to eat tomorrow, you need to let them act on that decision right now. That means either:

- **A reservation button** that connects to your booking system (OpenTable, Resy, or a simple form)
- **An online ordering link** for takeout/delivery (your own system, Toast, or even a direct link to your DoorDash/UberEats page — though we'll talk about why your own system is better in a minute)

The key word is "link." You don't necessarily need a full ordering system built into your website on day one. Even a prominent button that says "Order Online" and links to your existing ordering platform is better than making people search for it.

When we built the site for Chef's Delight — a personal chef service here in South Carolina — the booking flow was front and center. Visitors see available services, pick what they want, and request a booking without hunting through pages. The result: more bookings from the website, fewer "how do I book?" phone calls.

## 3. Hours, location, and schema markup

This sounds obvious, but you'd be surprised how many restaurant websites bury their hours on a separate "About" page or only show them in a footer that's hard to find on mobile.

Your hours and address should be visible on every single page — typically in the header or a sticky bar. And they need to be accurate. If you have holiday hours, seasonal hours, or different lunch/dinner hours, update them. Nothing tanks trust faster than driving across town to find a "Closed" sign when the website said you were open.

Behind the scenes, your developer should add **schema markup** — structured data that tells Google exactly what your hours are, where you're located, your price range, and your cuisine type. This is what powers those rich Google results that show hours and ratings right in the search listing. Without schema markup, Google is guessing. With it, Google knows.

## 4. Google Business Profile integration

Your Google Business Profile (GBP) is arguably more important than your website for local restaurant discovery. But they work together. Your website should:

- **Match your GBP information exactly** (name, address, phone, hours)
- **Link to your GBP** review page (making it easy for happy customers to leave reviews)
- **Use the same photos** you feature on GBP

Consistency between your website and your GBP signals to Google that your information is reliable. Mismatches — different hours, different phone numbers — create confusion for both Google and customers.

If you haven't claimed your Google Business Profile yet, stop reading this and go do it. It's free, and it's the single highest-impact marketing action a local restaurant can take. We wrote a [full guide to setting up your Google Business Profile](/blog/google-business-profile-guide-sc) if you need help.

## 5. A fast photo gallery

People eat with their eyes first, and this is doubly true online. Your website needs high-quality photos of your food, your space, and your team. But "high-quality" doesn't mean "massive file size."

A common mistake: uploading photos straight from a DSLR camera at 4000x3000 pixels and 5MB each. Load six of those on a page and you've got a 30MB page that takes 15 seconds to load on a phone. Your visitors are gone before the first image appears.

Properly optimized restaurant photos should be:
- **Resized** to the display size (usually 800-1200px wide is plenty)
- **Compressed** using modern formats like WebP (60-80% smaller than JPEG with no visible quality loss)
- **Lazy-loaded** (images below the fold load only when the visitor scrolls to them)

A well-optimized gallery page should load in under 2 seconds, even with 20+ photos. This is something your web developer handles at build time — you just provide the photos.

## 6. Email collection

Social media followers are rented. Email subscribers are owned. Instagram can change its algorithm tomorrow and cut your reach in half (it has, repeatedly). But an email list? That's yours.

Your website should have a simple, clear way for visitors to join your email list. This doesn't need to be a pop-up that covers the whole screen. A simple bar — "Get our weekly specials. Enter your email." — works. Position it after the menu section, where someone has already decided they like what you offer.

What to send: weekly specials, holiday menus, event announcements, and the occasional behind-the-scenes story. Keep it short, keep it regular, and always include a link to order or reserve.

## The DoorDash problem

A note about third-party platforms. DoorDash, UberEats, and Grubhub are useful for discovery — they put you in front of people who are browsing for delivery options. But they take 15-30% of every order. On a $50 order, that's $7.50-$15 going to the platform instead of your kitchen.

Your own website with a direct ordering link (even a simple form that sends you an email or text) keeps 100% of that revenue. The goal isn't to abandon DoorDash entirely — it's to gradually move your repeat customers to ordering directly. "Order from our website and get 10% off" is a simple, effective strategy.

## What this costs

A restaurant website with all six of these elements fits comfortably in our Business tier: $1,800-$3,500 depending on complexity. That includes the menu page, photo gallery, reservation/ordering integration, schema markup, mobile optimization, and email signup. Hosted on Cloudflare's global CDN, so it loads fast everywhere.

If you need a full online ordering system with payment processing through Stripe, that's on the higher end. If you just need a great menu page with links to your existing platforms, that's on the lower end.

Either way, it pays for itself. One extra table a week from better Google visibility covers the investment in a few months.

## Your website is your host

Think of your website as the digital version of your host stand. It's the first interaction most customers have with your restaurant. It should be warm, clear, fast, and helpful — just like a good host.

If your current site isn't doing that job, [tell us about your restaurant](/get-started). We'll build something that works as hard as your kitchen does.
